\subtree{\title{"How possible" questions}

\p{General form: X makes Y seem impossible, yet nevertheless Y is possible.}
\ul{
  \li{Can't we just reject X because we take Y to be possible, which contradicts taking X seriously?}}
\p{Y="how is freedom possible?", X = "we are chemical/physical beings"}
\p{"how is knowledge of the external world possible?"}
\p{X = skepticism "How do you know you're not dreaming / in the Matrix?"}
\ul{
\li{you don't independently know that you're not in the Matrix / [brain in the vat](phil-0040), so how could you know that your hand is in front of you?}
\li{The skeptic has put an insuperable requirement for knowledge of the external world}
\ul{
  \li{Possible replies:}
  \li{Say the requirement is not genuine}
  \ul{
    \li{More promising since requirements are usually designed to be unfulfillable (though they still are very compelling)}
  }      \li{Challenge the word "independently"}
  \ul{
    \li{challenging skeptic's assumed notions of epistemic priority because you are accused of question begging if you say "I know I have a hand, so therefore I'm not a handless brain in a vat"}
  }        \li{GE Moore strategy: argue from knowledge to knowledge rather from ignorance to ignorance.}
  \li{Say we can satisfy the requirement}
