\subtree{\title{Kant: 'grandfather of how possible questions' and inventor of trancendental arguments}
  \p{How is mathematical knowledge possible? How is pure science possible?}
  \ul{
    \li{For the former, Kant answers by drawing attention to how diagramatic reasoning is crucial.}
    \li{One can respond to how diagrams (with, say, specific triangles) could prove general properties (e.g. about triangles in general) and Kant has a response.}
  }\p{He's not asking from an epistemological perspective.}
  \p{These are interesting b/c they are examples of synthetic a priori}
  \ul{
    \li{How is that kind of knowledge possible? (given that it must be possible in virtue of mathematical knowledge existing)}
    \li{X = "where does the knowledge come from if not experience nor analysis of concepts?"}
  }
  \p{Trancendental argument:}
  \ul{
    \li{start off with assumption we have a certain experience, then try to find necessary conditions for us to have that experience}
    \li{E.g. external world skeptics believe we have inner experience. Kant argues that outer experience is a necessary precondition for inner experience. Therefore we have knowledge of the external world.}
    \ul{
      \li{This doesn't answer the 'how possible' question. It shows that Y is true but does not dissolve the obstacle X. So again we have something that seems necessarily true that asserts something that's possible is impossible. The skeptic has the upper hand since their arguments aren't as abstract / untrustworthy.}
      \li{But it's not like Kant thinks his trancendental arguments were designed to answer his 'how possible' questions (some commentators make the mistake of assuming this).}
    }
  }}